{"parentUuid":"c149358c-3a0e-4189-9da9-84e70338af9a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"db363b7a-2eac-4613-9175-6b4538fab4c5","agentId":"a4f8f31128338bb55","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011ngobiqShZVQVwYyVDwg7Y","type":"tool_result","content":"eval_metadata.json\noutputs","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"883c9ec8-edca-4ac7-8294-9693a9b693a3","timestamp":"2026-04-28T12:30:36.341Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c149358c-3a0e-4189-9da9-84e70338af9a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/Users/edeno/Documents/GitHub/spyglass-skill","sessionId":"1f8c4ccf-12e2-4179-973b-7ba51de72be5","version":"2.1.119","gitBranch":"master","slug":"rippling-forging-crane"}
{"parentUuid":"883c9ec8-edca-4ac7-8294-9693a9b693a3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a4f8f31128338bb55","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01QGukmp6tuvBDkHYtwYBbzn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Q3TeoGjv9iXNgobzQ5BC3f","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/edeno/Documents/GitHub/spyglass-skill/skills/spyglass-workspace/iteration-2/eval-077-schema-part-tables-probe/without_skill/outputs/response.md","content":"# Part tables of `Probe`\n\nIn DataJoint, every table class exposes a `parts()` classmethod (and, equivalently, an instance method) that returns the part tables attached to it as a master. So the one-liner is just:\n\n```python\nProbe.parts()\n```\n\nThat returns the part-table classes (or their full table names, depending on the `as_objects` flag) that hang off `Probe`.\n\nA couple of common variants if you want the Python classes back rather than the raw `__` table names:\n\n```python\nProbe.parts(as_objects=True)          # list of part-table classes\n[p.__name__ for p in Probe.parts(as_objects=True)]   # just the short names\n```\n\n## The two parts on `Probe`\n\nIn `Master.Part` notation:\n\n- `Probe.Shank`\n- `Probe.Electrode`\n\n`Probe` itself stores one row per probe type (probe id, manufacturer, num shanks, etc.). `Probe.Shank` enumerates the shanks belonging to each probe, and `Probe.Electrode` enumerates the individual electrode/contact sites on those shanks. Those are the only two part tables defined on `Probe` — there aren't any other `Probe.*` parts to list.\n\nIf you wanted to confirm interactively without trusting memory, `Probe.parts()` (or `dj.Diagram(Probe)` in a notebook, which draws the master plus its parts) is the source of truth.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":221,"cache_read_input_tokens":22574,"output_tokens":615,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_reque